{
  "texts": [
    "These role definitions may lead models to generate overly coherent or stereotypical responses, especially when prompts rely on coarse identity categories.",
    "For example, studies have shown that LLMs often exaggerate ideological consistency or cultural traits when simulating politically or racially marked personas [29,23].",
    "This mirrors concerns in survey methodology where respondent categories-like \"Latino voters\"-mask within-group heterogeneity.",
    "Bias from the Model AlgorithmEven with identical prompts, different LLMs may produce systematically different outputs depending on architectural decisions, model size, and decoding strategies.",
    "Shin et al. [34] demonstrate that various LLMs carry default associations about social groups-e.g., linking political conservatism with specific moral traits-that persist across generations."
  ]
}